      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your current brute-force solution is O(n³), which will definitely fail the 1-second limit for 100,000 characters. To pass, you need to use the Manacher's algorithm, which runs in O(n) time. Here is the optimized implementation using that approach:\n\n```python\ndef longest_palindrome(s):\n    if not s: return \"\"\n    t = '#'.join('^{}$'.format(s))\n    n = len(t)\n    p = [0] * n\n    c, r = 0, 0\n    for i in range(n):\n        mirror = 2 * c - i\n        if i < r:\n            p[i] = min(r - i, p[mirror])\n        while t[i + 1 + p[i]] == t[i - 1 - p[i]]:\n            p[i] += 1\n        if i + p[i] > r:\n            c, r = i, i + p[i]\n    return s[:p.index(max(p)) // 2 + 1]\n```\nThis reduces the complexity from cubic to linear, ensuring it passes strict time limits even",
